fotd 2: Mathematician GH Hardy invited Srinivasa Ramanujan to Cambridge after he sent a letter filled with equations that Hardy could not prove, to which Hardy responded “They must be true because if not, no one would have the imagination to invent them.” At Cambridge, Ramanujan would write amazing theorems he claimed to receive from divine inspiration and Hardy and others would spend months trying to prove them.

fotd 3: After getting my flu shot, the Yale medical school student nurse said “I can’t find where I put the needle in so I’m going to put the bandaid on somewhere randomly” and then completely missed.

fotd 4: Last month, astronomers at two separate observatories announced that phosphine, which is produced only through biotic processes on Earth, had been discovered on Venus at an extremely high 15-sigma confidence level. But a few days ago a new paper claimed that the original team analyzed the data wrongly and in fact the confidence is less than 2-sigma, making it a non-detection.

fotd 5: Today during my Japanese oral test I said “I don’t know” when she asked what I was doing for winter break and then said “eating Christmas food” when she asked what I was doing for Christmas. Then she was confused and asked what Christmas food was and I didn’t even know so I just said “meat.” So definitely did not do too good there.

fotd 6: The false detection of phosphine on Venus is similar to another “discovery” about 6 years ago, where scientists thought they had detected signals from gravitational waves in the Cosmic Microwave Background at 7-sigma confidence, which would have been extremely strong evidence for the Big Bang. Reanalysis and observations from a later, more sensitive telescope confirmed that the signal they originally detected could be completely attributed to cosmic dust.

fotd 10: St Augustine’s Confessions is considered to be the first Western autobiography and also one of the most important pieces of Western literature. In it he describes his transition from a promiscuous, hedonistic lifestyle (examples he gives are stealing for fun and disobeying his mother’s advice to “never defile another man’s wife”) to Christianity, giving a guide for others to convert. Fun quote: “When my father saw me at the baths, now growing towards manhood,...he, already hence anticipating his descendants, gladly told it to my mother”

fotd 12: Mary Shelley had an…interesting relationship with her family. Her mother, Mary Wollstonecraft, died from a childbirth infection. Meanwhile, Percy Shelley, Mary’s future husband, was out of contact with his family after being expelled from Oxford. He eloped with and quickly married Harriet Westbrook, who was 16 at the time. He then became a pupil of William Godwin, Mary’s father, where he met and fell in love with Mary, taking her virginity on Wollstonecraft’s grave and also leaving Harriet after she became pregnant. Percy and Mary eloped, bringing along one of Mary’s half-sisters, but within two months, they returned broke, and Godwin kicked them out. Later, Mary’s other half-sister committed suicide because she was in love with Percy and Harriet drowned herself. Sounds exciting.

fotd 13: The solution to the rotation of solid bodies in 3 dimensions is famously messy. Maxwell suggested that “it had never been thoroughly understood by any but the most expert mathematicians.” It is even used as a metaphor in Middlemarch, one of the greatest English novels: “In short, woman was a problem which, since Brooke's mind fell blank before it, could be hardly less complicated than the revolutions of an irregular solid.”

fotd 16: Scott Joplin’s “Great Crush Collision March” was based on a publicity stunt done by the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad. One of the company’s agents, William Crush, had the great idea of having a public staged train crash. 40,000 people attended, but when the trains collided, their boilers exploded, sending debris into the crowd killing and injuring multiple people. Crush was fired that day, but was rehired the next day after no negative publicity came out. The event was a huge success for the company, giving them international recognition.

fotd 23: Fibrodysplasia ossificans progressiva is the only known disease in which one organ system turns into another. fotd 31: Depending on which axiom of set theory you use, the number of field automorphisms of the complex numbers varies. If you use the axiom of choice (equivalent to every vector space has a basis), then there are uncountably infinite of them. But if you use the axiom of determinancy (equivalent to every game that can’t end in a tie has a winning strategy), there are only two.
